Hi [PERSON_NAME], [PERSON_NAME], and [PERSON_NAME],

Everyone worked hard today--and for 2 hours!  I'm guessing [PERSON_NAME] is spent!   The initial session is always the longest and hardest, as I'm trying to put all the pieces of the picture together.  Normally I charge $85/for that first session, but I just looked back through my notes and see that I said $75, so $75 it is.  Normally, it's $85 for the first session, and $75 for subsequent sessions.

I forgot to get a check from you (we were all exhausted!) and I was thinking more about your little girl sacked out next to me.

REVIEW:

[PERSON_NAME] is an absolute DELIGHT, and she has landed herself in the best of families!  That is so exciting to see, and I so enjoyed meeting all 3 of you.

I don't see ANY negative qualities in Rosie--and given the fact that she went for 2 hours, and was still looking to me for direction--shows that she is smart and willing and zero stubborn. 
I'm sorry that anyone buzzed her, or advised you to use a spike collar.  There is no need for those devices, whatsoever.  [PERSON_NAME] is crazy about both of you, and she will continue to eagerly learn because it's fun.  It should always be fun, and positive, positive, positive!!!  

You'll need to order a nylon slip collar lead online, or have me do it for you.  The goal is to walk her with a loose leash so everyone is in harmony.  Corrections are not punitive--they are merely to get her attention, and to get her to re-focus.  Corrections must always be followed by praise since no one, no dog, wants to be corrected, then comply, and not get a reward.

Again the timing is quick correction, then immediate reward the split second she starts to comply.  If you get into a pulling contest, or she's choking herself, it's time to regroup.  I don't want you to ever be in a pulling contest with her.  

[PERSON_NAME], you did a great job today and I know it felt awkward.  Remember:
1   &quoteLet's go,&quote
2.  Step forward with your left foot.

Use a cheerful &quotelet's go&quote and pat your left leg if you don't have her immediate attention.  Remember, every correction is followed by praise so, if you need to do a correction, do so briefly, and then reward her behavior.  For the time being, skip using treats with her on walks until you've got the timing of the whole thing down.  Treats at the wrong time, or treats used as encouragement, can sometimes have the reverse effect as in, the dog doesn't want to do anything until she gets a treat.  Let's not set up that dynamic.

When you get back from walks and take off the leash, say &quotefree time!&quote and be a little playful and lovey.  She needs to understand the difference between paying attention to you, and relaxing.

Label all behaviors!  Work on &quotepotty&quote or whatever word you want, but repeat it when she is going to the bathroom with &quotegood potty, good potty,&quote the goal is to get her to understand what the word means, so she can also understand when NOT to potty.  We're simply increasing her understanding of the world around her without using force or punishment.

So when she goes to the back door in the morning, ask her if she has to go potty, repeat the question, follow her out and don't say anything until she potties--then exuberantly reward her with &quotegood potty!!  good potty!!&quote

Label &quotethirsty,&quote &quotewater,&quote &quotesupper&quote or whatever word you use, and &quotehungry.&quote  If she lies down, say &quotegood down.&quote  It doesn't matter if she doesn't have a clue what she's done right, she'll develop associations with words.

Try NOT to say &quotecome.&quote  It has no meaning for her, and repeating it  over and over makes the word loose it's interest.  I always start with &quotecloser&quote and a hand signal, so that the dog gets the idea of moving closer to me is good, and rewarded.  We'll go over that next time.

Touching her feet:  keep it quick and simple, and only do it when she's relaxed.  Hold on to her foot gently and tell her good girl.  If she tries to pull away, don't let her, and don't say &quotegood girl&quote during that time.  When she relaxes, let go.  Her reward for relaxing is you letting go.  It's the same concept as the correction when walking--a quick correction, then immediate reward when she gives in.  The timing is important.  We'll work on that.

If she's allowed to come up on the sofa, I might think about adding another step to the process.  First, she sits.  Then you say, &quoteup!&quote and pat the sofa, or your lap, and encourage her to come up.  Again, we're creating a language between you, and dogs see you much more as a &quot[PERSON_NAME],&quote when they understand what you want.

Similarly, I would introduce an &quoteoff,&quote NOT DOWN, an &quoteoff,&quote for times when you are getting her off the sofa.  Like everything else, it is said in a pleasant voice, and as soon as she is off, &quotegood off, good off.&quote  We'll do some of that next time.

If she's concerned about household items--broom, vacuum, etc.,--never force her to face her fears.  It's a backfire approach that actually can build a dog's fears.

By creating a language, and using positive and rewarding leadership, [PERSON_NAME] is going to be even happier.  There is no reason in the world that she should &quoteknow&quote not to potty in your friend's house.  So, first, we need to teach her what the words mean.  She didn't do it to be evil, or bad.  I expect there was some other factor at play such as she was wound up, or didn't know why she was in a different house.  Remember, you've only been her family for 6 weeks and I wouldn't be surprised if changes worry her a little.  

Keep an eye on that right back knee, and make note of any tenderness.

Remember to positively reinforce anything and everything she does--for instance, is she just happens to be sitting, tell her &quotegood sit!&quote  Avoid saying &quoteno,&quote she has no idea what she's supposed to do instead of why ever you are telling her &quoteno.&quote  There is a place for &quoteno,&quote but not until we increase her understanding.

[PERSON_NAME] what causes water pressure to drop is buildup. Something getting flushed down toilet wont cause water pressure to drop. Is it cold water, hot water or both that pressure has been lost?

It seems to be both.  The pipes are pretty old.  There were some issues a while back, and we were told that they will probably need to be replaced soon because they are quite old.  However that will cost $30k and we are going to sell the house soon so that didn't make a lot of sense for us.  the pressure has been fine since then, they cleaned out the pipes a bit.  However since flushing that down the toilet the water pressure has declined again, so it seemed like too much of a coincidence to be unrelated

If they were charging you 30k its probably to redo it copper which is very expensive. You can go with alternatives like pex pipe and cpvc. But like i said stuff flushed down toilet is going to the sewage only thing that could happen from flushing something that shouldnt down toilet would be a stoppage the sewer and water pipe is two complete different systems.

You can give me call and we can talk more about it. Usually to prevent stuff like this from happening is adding a whole house water filter or a water softener but that only good when the house is first built because later on when pressure is decreased the damage is done. If you do try to sell the house when the home inspector checks it out if the pressure is too weak they will want it corrected before being to sell it

MAC AND CHZ (double for large pan)



Ingredients

1 stick butter, sliced, plus more for greasing
2 tablespoons sea salt 
1 tablespoon vegetable oil 
1 pound elbow noodles
1 stick unsalted butter, melted
3 large eggs, whisked
1/2 teaspoon black pepper 
4 cups shredded muenster cheese
1 cup of evaporated milk
1 cup heavy cream 


Directions

Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Grease a square with butter.

Bring a large stockpot of water to a boil with the sea salt and oil. Add the noodles and cook for 7 minutes. Drain and cool the pasta. Place layer of butter pieces munster chz on bottom of pan light coat of evaporated milk, lay noodles on top, repeat same layer over and over til top of pan, evenly over top chz layer pour egg&heavy cream mixture. Sprinkle the dish with the remaining 1/4 teaspoon black pepper and 1/4 teaspoon seasoned salt….

Cover with foil bake for 35mins uncover bake additional 10 mins...

Tomato, Cucumber, Avocado SaladThis tomato, cucumber, avocado salad is an easy, flavorful summer salad. 

Prep Time: 12 mins
Cook Time: 0 mins
Total Time: 12 minutes
Yield: 4
Category: Salad
Cuisine: Mediterranean
Ingredients

1 1/2 cups of chopped tomatoes – I used cherry tomatoes
1 cucumber – peeled and seeded then diced
1 avocado – diced
4 oz feta cheese – cubed
1 handful parsley – minced – about 2 tbs
2 tbs olive oil
1 tbs red wine vinegar
8 twists of black pepper from a pepper milll

For the Cucumbers
16–20 (½ -inch-thick) English cucumber slices
2 Tbsp. extra-virgin olive oil
2 Tbsp. freshly squeezed lime juice
½ tsp. sea salt½ tsp. pepper
1?3 cup chopped cilantro
For the Blackened Shrimp
2 tsp. paprika
2 tsp. onion powder
1 tsp. garlic powder
1 tsp. cumin
1 tsp. sea salt
1 tsp. pepper
1 tsp. dried ground thyme
1 tsp. dried ground oregano
¼ to ½ tsp. cayenne (adjust to your heat index)
¼ to ½ tsp. red chili flakes (adjust to your heat index)
16–20 (about 1¼ lbs. total) large deveined tail-on shrimp
2 Tbsp. butter

Put the sliced cukes in a bowl and mix with the olive oil, lime juice, salt, pepper, and cilantro. Cover and refrigerate until ready to serve.
Prepare the blackening seasoning by combining the paprika, onion powder, garlic powder, cumin, sea salt, pepper, thyme, oregano, cayenne, and red chili flakes in a shallow baking dish or pie plate; blend together well. Coat the shrimp with cooking spray and put a few at a time in the blackening seasoning to coat all over. Set aside. Repeat until all the shrimp are coated.
In a large (10- to 12-inch) heavy skillet melt the butter over medium heat. Let the skillet get hot. Place a few shrimp in (don’t crowd) and pan-sear on each side for 1½ to 2 min-utes. Remove seared shrimp to a plate. If you need to add cooking spray to the skillet to keep it from sticking, have at it. Serve the blackened shrimp with the cucumbers on the side (I serve the shrimp on top of each cucumber slice).

The quote does not include the cost of new hardware or if drilling mounting holes and filling old holes is required, this would also effect the price. I do not support restrictive dieting because the body's natural response is to increase cravings that lead to binge eating. Binge eating disorder is the fastest growing eating disorder in the country and it's because of dieting. You can eat your Chinese food and we will just focus on the habits that will help you change the way you approach food over time. It will reduce your cravings for foods that maybe aren't serving you to eat them on a regular basis or in large amounts, but absolutely nothing is off limits. It happens to 98% of dieters so I offer a different approach to accommodate the body's natural response to put weight back on and try to nip it in the bud before it feels like you've lost control. I do this because I learned this the hard way with both myself and seeing it happen in my clients and my friends clients and then put all my focus and education into disordered eating patterns and their relationship to common weight loss techniques. It's my goal to help prevent rebound weight gain before it starts and to promote body acceptance so that people aren't easily sucked into silly weight loss schemes that do more harm than good. Since you will have separate programs I can't give one program to the both of you, but I can offer you two a family discount of $139 for nutrition and $169 for nutrition and workouts. Then I use that information to design your fitness program and give you a quick start food guide to give you an idea of how to structure your meals for your specific needs. It's not meant to be strict though. Just something to practice. Then you take on a new habit every two weeks. These habits are meant to transform how you approach food for long term sustained health. Behavior science regularly shows that working on one new habit at a time is the absolute best way to ensure lasting changes. Complete life overhauls just don't work. It's deceptively simple yet you get to remain actively engaged and accountable with the lessons and check ins. If you're interested I can shoot you both your invites now. I just need your full names and emails. I do my billing through PayPal invoicing so that is done easily and securely, as well. It's been great to learn so much about you and your husband! [PERSON_NAME], are you still seeing BBs in your bedroom?  With two treatments in your bedroom and with encasements on the mattress and boxsprings your problem should be at a minimum in that room.  

As for the LR there has been no treatment done in that room.  It's good what you have seen appear  to have been affected  by the treatment upstairs.  How the BBs came to be in the LR is the important question.  Since you saw them on the walls and not on/in the couches suggest that they may have traveled from the BR to the LR and are not residing in the couch.  

The LR has not been treated because up to this point no BB activity has been observed in that room.  I do not treat room that show no BB activity for several reasons:
(1) keep the overall cost down
(2) keep the amount of chemicals applied into a house to a minimum

With that being said I would suggest I come in and inspect the LR and the couches and treat accordingly.  

The same protocol would be in effect though that I can steam and chemically treat the couches and baseboards in the LR but the room needs to be vacated for a few hours.  The MBR would be inspected as well.  There is another item you may want to consider: a BB lure-trap.  It  emits a small amount of CO2 and thus attracts BBs 24/7.  Combined with a chemical treatment it works well.  The lures need to be changed out every 30 days.  If you are interested in those I would suggest two months worth (minimum) for placement in your BR (2) and in the living room under the couch (2).  I can give you a price and have them here in approx 7 working days.  Let me know how many months of protection would would like.    

Let me know what you are thinking.?

I've only seen one in our bedroom since you came and did the treatment.  I think at this point what I would like to do is get you to come out and reinspect and get an estimate for the lures and further treatment.  Is that acceptable?

Hi [PERSON_NAME],

Thanks so much for getting in touch! You caught me at a great time, just posting some last minute edits before the weekend starts.

The amount of edits can be hard to say exactly. There are so many factors such as how long we are there, the number of guests, how long the reception is. In our contracts, we estimate 400-750, but the least I've ever delivered was around 600. The last wedding, I delivered 1200. 

After the wedding I sit down and go through all my photos and pull out duplicates (for a first kiss I may take 40 to make sure I get &quotethe one&quote and then pull the 4-5 best of these). Once I've narrowed it down, EVERY one of those images is edited. That is 6-8 weeks on editing. Those images are then posted in an online gallery you can share with family, and also given to you on either USB or download.

The remaining photos are kept on file but not given to the client. As an industry standard, photographers don't typically share unedited images with clients without charging a pricey fee. That being said, I always try to over deliver and not deprive clients of special moments just because they aren't the most &quoteartful&quote shot. I typically just pull the more unflattering versions of moments :) I generally try to deliver around twice that expected, though that obviously can't be promised. Some photographers feel too many options overloads the clients, but I'd rather you have too many than not enough!

[PERSON_NAME],
I woould like to start with anxiety separation lessons . How much would that cost ? And how many lessons  we would need ?

Hi [PERSON_NAME],

There are not specific lessons for separation anxiety.   That is something that improves overtime while working your dog through obedience and general behavior modification (correcting problem behaviors) and by managing certain behaviors and issues.  There is no quick fix for separation anxiety, but by working through properly taught obedience training, your dog learns to trust you, listen to you, respect boundaries/understand what is allowed and not, and that you will always come back.  That is how you work through the issues you are having.  

Below is the general information on the different programs I offer.  Take a look at the different programs and let me know if you have any additional questions or would like to get started.  I'm happy to help anyway I can.
__________________________________________

I offer 3 levels of obedience training. Each level and its description is listed below. Each level of training is 8 weeks in length, and the length of the class and your homework lessons will depend on what level you are at in the training.  You will be instructed on any behavior modification needed (ex: aggression) at no additional charge, however I do require that all my students be enrolled in obedience to receive behavior modification as obedience always helps with behavior.
 
Basic Obedience (8 Weeks):
By the end of basic obedience, your dog will be able to perform all of the following tasks on a 6 ft. leash:
Loose leash walking (no pulling on the leash)
Heel
Sit
Down
Stay
Recall
 
Intermediate (8-16 Weeks):
By the end of intermediate obedience, your dog will be able to perform all of the following tasks with only a collar on (no leash).
Heel freely
Sit on command (in motion and stationary)
Down on command (in motion and stationary)
Sit stay for 5 minutes at a distance of 50 ft
Down stay for 30 minutes at a distance of 100 ft
Recall from 100 ft
 
Advanced (8 Weeks +):
By the end of advanced obedience, your dog will be able to perform all of the following tasks WITHOUT leash or collar.
Heel freely
Sit on command (in motion and stationary)
Down on command (in motion and stationary)
Sit stay for 20 minutes maximum out of sight and scent of the handler
Down stay for 45 minutes minimum out of sight and scent of the handler
Recall from any distance
 
All of this will be done around any and all distractions and your dog will respond to your command the first time, every time you command it.
 
The training is held outdoors in ANY and ALL weather conditions.

Pricing is as follows:

Group lessons:
1st dog: $350 per level of obedience
Each Additional Dog: $175 per level

Private Lessons:
1st dog: $1000 per level
Each Additional Dog: $500 per level
(Additional travel fee will be charged if classes are not held at Bastrop Location)

Board & Train:
$1500 per month, one month minimum required (standard 4x10 inside climate controlled kennel)
$1800 per month, one month minimum required (6x10 semi-private bunglaow with 6x5 inside climate controlled portion and doggy door to outside 6x5 fully enclosed patio)
($750 deposit required at time of reservation, remainder due at drop off)

If you are not providing food for your dog during their stay, and additional $60 will be added to cover food expenses.  If your dog is on medications or requiring treatment of any kind during it's stay, other than flea/tick and heartworm prevention which is REQUIRED, please let us know ahead of time so we can make sure it is something we can accommodate and discuss any appropriate fees.  Your dog must be up to date on rabies and distemper/parvo before it's stay with us.  If your dog has recieved the bordatella vaccine, we will not board your dog until 2 weeks after the vaccine was administered. 

If your dog is coming for board and train primarily for behavioral issues and not for general obedience (i.e. dog aggression, aggression toward people, resource guarding), there will be an additional $500 fee as these issues take more individual time which restricts the number of other board and trains I can take on and present more risks to both my animals and myself as the dogs will require exposure to other animals and people to trigger this behavior for correction.

All enrollment fees are due to before beginning class and are non-refundable.  You can prepay online through the enrollment forms or you can bring your payment to the first class. If you prepay, please bring your receipt to the first class.

Group Class Locations:

Tuesday nights:   7:30 PM [LOCATION] (Private Residence) 
Saturday:  [LOCATION]  (Private residence)
 
I generally recommend group lessons to my clients as you will get some really good distractions at least once a week with the other dogs and people that come to the class, and you get to see that everyone in the class deals with the same &quotehurdles&quote, frustrations, and struggles that you do! (It usually helps to have a support group around! :-) ) If you do want more one on one attention, though, we can do private lessons, or you can add additional private lessons to any group package for a discounted rate of $50 per lesson.  That's completely up to you and your personal comfort level.  I do also require all new students to start with the basic classes so that I know all instruction has been given properly from the start.
 
I am not sure if you have watched the videos on my site, but if you have you will know what an advanced dog looks like.

Let me know if you are interested in the training and what type of lessons you would like so we can make arrangements to get you started.  You will also need to make sure you have the proper equipment ahead of time.

Equipment needed:

6 ft LEATHER or LEATHER ALTERNATIVE (biothane leash)
  ---PLEASE no nylon or chain leashes.  ABSOLUTELY NO RETRACTABLE LEASHES!
  ---Leash must be stitched or riveted.  Do not purchase a leash that is braided or has braiding.

Prong Collar
  ---This is required of all students enrolled.
  ---DO NOT get a quick release/easy release collar
  ---Prong Collar should be all metal. NO PLASTIC OR NYLON COLLARS
  ---Please purchase the smallest size you can for your dog.  You can always add links to make  the collar bigger.  (ex:  get a 14&quote collar if your dog has a 16&quote neck and just add links).
  ---Picture of appropriate style of collar found here:  https://leerburg.com/photos/Titan_Reg_01.jpg
  ---DO NOT purchase a prong collar from Petco.  They are not durable.

Choke Chain
  ---Required for dogs showing ANY sign of aggression
  ---Get the thinnest chain available for the length needed (ex: If 20&quote collar is available in 2.5 mm and 3mm, get the 2.5 mm)
  ---Get the shortest chain possible that you can slide over your dog's head.  It should be tight to get on, and seem difficult to pull off.  There should be as little slack as possible on the chain when it is around the dog's neck.

Hi [PERSON_NAME], thank you for getting back to me with that information. This is definitely something I can help you with. 

Our method is called Natural Canine Behavior Rehabilitation. This method is based on a dog's instinct, and does not rely on punishment/fear/dominance or conditioning/obedience to teach the dog what it is supposed to do. Obedience does not equal good behavior, and dominance/fear can worsen the actual causes of bad behavior. The beauty of our method is that we teach you why unwanted behaviors happen, in addition to how to fix them, so you gain the ability to assess any behaviors that you notice (even if initially you didn't realize they were bothering you), and you can understand why they happen as well as how to fix them.

Unlike [PERSON_NAME] and similar dominance theory trainers, we do not believe that our role is to be the [PERSON_NAME] and to be dominant over our dogs. Current research supports steering away from dominance theory, as well. We are not a dog and do not need to be a &quotepack member&quote in the sense of another dog. We are human and dogs are dogs. They simply need to respect us, our space, our property, and our rules - they don't need to submit to us. If we use dominance to combat what may be dominant behaviors, we could end up in a couple of scenarios - either the dog submits and is fearful of us (not what we want if we are trying to build trust and respect) or the dog challenges us and we end up with bites and an even more dominant (or aggressive) dog.

We do not use shock or prong collars because these collars correct through pain and/or startling the dog, which does not help the dog trust us (essential for good behavior). Additionally these tools punish a dog for acting on their instinct, when they don't know any better. Instead, we need to work with their instinct in order to shape it into something that will encourage good behavior. Often, a dog who does not view the human as the leader will have &quotedominant&quote behaviors, which are incompatible with living with humans. We help you re-wire your dog's instinct so that they don't feel the need to be a leader, and so that they trust you and respect you.

Conversely, we don't teach a dog to do something it should be doing naturally (like walking with a loose leash) by giving commands - then you always have to ask for good behavior - or by feeding them treats - once the treats stop, the behavior is likely to return. This is because they were never taught in their own language and they were never taught why these things are expected of them. That &quotewhy&quote doesn't just come from telling them &quotebecause I said so,&quote it comes from setting them up as a follower but also setting yourself up as a leader - dogs naturally follow the leader. So, while we have to teach your dog to follow, we also have to teach you to be a calm, confident leader!

Additionally, when a dog is excited or stressed, they go into instinct mode. This means that they are operating solely on their instinct, and anything they have learned (i.e. obedience) will go out the window because it isn't instinctive - no matter how flawless their obedience is. All of these approaches address the symptoms of larger behavioral issues (i.e. body posture - sitting rather than jumping) but don't address the behavior issue itself (why the dog is jumping in the first place) so especially in instinct mode, the root behavior issues will still be present.

We see issues with leadership (the major root of many behavior issues) quite often - owners don't mean to, but all that many people have been taught, such as obedience, actually sends subliminal messages to the dog that tell the dog they are in charge. We don't fight your dog for that leadership role, because your dog naturally wants to be a follower, and to be allowed to just be a dog. When your dog feels the need to be the leader - protector, provider, etc. - that's when behavior issues will start to present themselves, whether it is through pulling at the leash or jumping, or something even worse like reactivity or aggression. When they feel protected, they will slip naturally into that follower role. Again, we don't want to use dominance, because part of teaching a dog that we are protecting them is to teach them that they can trust us - a dog who is afraid of someone won't trust that person.

I help you make simple changes to some of your daily routines and help you learn appropriate responses to unwanted behaviors, as well as set some boundaries in order to have your dog become a follower instead of a leader. With rules in the home and on walks, it isn't about giving a command and telling dogs to do a specific behavior...it's not about what they *do*, it's about what they *don't* do. Take jumping for example - obedience method tells you to tell a jumping dog to sit. This is bad for a few reasons. First, when you give a dog any attention, you reward that behavior. So, by looking at the dog and giving commands, the dog is being rewarded for the jump that got him attention in the first place. Then, we tell the dog to sit, but they didn't learn anything - they weren't taught not to jump by telling them to sit, and even if they know &quoteoff&quote they still don't naturally stay off and instead have to be told &quoteoff&quote any time they jump - they just may be great at listening and get off immediately, but the jumping is still there (because it's the instinct of a dog who is a leader to show others he is their leader by jumping on them). Taking it a step further, dog jumps, human gives attention (reward), tells dog to sit, dog gets treat (reward). So you have taught the dog that jumping ultimately gets a treat. That doesn't work to teach them not to jump, but if they are perfect with obedience, they may stop when you ask them to. When you insert a more stressful situation, the obedience doesn't work anymore, because they are in pure instinct mode. In reality, we don't &quoteneed&quote the dog to sit, we just need them not to jump, so if we eliminate the jumping (by becoming the non-dominant leader - dogs naturally don't jump on their leader), then we have accomplished our goal and not had potentially negative effects on long-term progress!

All of this is not to say that we never reward a dog! Part of our approach also requires you to reward good behavior (i.e. calmly petting when the dog is calm and relaxed), and spending lots of quality time loving on the dog, etc. The dog is supposed to be a member of your family!

In our class, we go over all of these factors and much more (about 4 hours' worth of material and hands-on practice), which will help you build a solid foundation on which to build good behavior. The class sets you up to not only solve any current issues and set your dog up for future success, but also to solve any other unwanted behaviors in or out of the home, and to prevent new behaviors from appearing. We cover topics including how a dog thinks, why they act how they do, how they communicate with one another (and how you can communicate most effectively with them), how to set boundaries and set up rules (including which boundaries and rules are absolutely essential to good behavior), as well as other factors which can impact behavior such as health and nutrition.

As for pricing, this class typically costs $750 since there is no aggression history. This is a one-time fee, and you should never have to hire another behavior trainer for the rest of his life since you will be equipped with the knowledge and tool set to handle him through anything. With our class, we also include our lifetime guarantee, which means that should these issues not go away with the initial approach we take, I will come back and tweak our approach as much as is needed, provided you continue to follow our advice and approach. You will also have me on call for the rest of his life, even if new issues should arise, or if your lifestyle changes in such a way that triggers new or re-occurring unwanted behaviors. If the financial aspect is a problem at all, please do not hesitate to let me know and I will do all I can to work with you on that!

All of our classes are private, in-home, with just myself (potentially a coworker from time to time), your family, and your dog, and the initial class usually lasts in the range of 3-4 hours. This ensures you get as much time as you need to fully understand the material, have hands-on practice, and ask all the questions you can come up with. We usually schedule initial classes on weekends so that everyone has the full 3-4 hours to commit to learning.

Let me know if you have any questions or concerns, and if you would like to proceed with our services. I look forward to hearing from you!

We carry Suntek, Madico and now [PERSON_NAME] films. Typically the darker the film is, the more heat rejection you'll get. Unless you are using a nano-technology film. For example UltraVision from Suntek will reduce the heat by about 54% and will let in about 53% of the light. I consider that one the best of both worlds. It's actually a very light film.
